<dl id="s12001cp"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us12" href="#s12001cp">Cyclops: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s12all.htm#s12001cp">sector 1(cp)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ribbonmen <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="s12001cp"> <li>Ulysses proto </li><li><ms href="#s12001cp">MS V.A.6-8</ms> </li><li>JJA 13:134h </li><li><a name="n1H1dy" href="../udra/u12da.htm#n1h1dy">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/n/n1h1yd.htm#s12001cp">Draft: 12H.1+</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">It will be noted that the opening observation is always of a harmless commonplace nature, which if addressed to a stranger could occasion no suspicion. &ldquo;The winter is approaching&rdquo; is a remark not out of course in October. If the immediate response is, &ldquo;It is time to expect it,&rdquo; the first speaker has reason to think he is talking to a brother <mark>Ribbonman</mark>. To make sure, he proceeds with a remark not likely to be understood unless by a fellow-member: &ldquo;Our foe is found out.&rdquo; A reply declaring that &ldquo;Our guardians are watchful&rdquo; establishes brotherhood between the parties. <small> A.M. Sullivan, <a name="AMSN" href="/udra/udex.htm#amsn"><cite title="source">New Ireland</cite></a> (1878), 57</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
